### Affected versions

JeecgBoot 3.9.2

### Summary

When the chat assistant in the AI Application Portal sends a message, it first adds the user input to the frontend chat list and renders it in the user message bubble. The user message branch does not perform HTML escaping. It only replaces line breaks with `<br>` and then writes the content into the page through `v-html`.

As a result, when a logged-in user sends content containing an HTML event attribute in the chat box, such as `<img src=x onerror=...>`, the script is executed immediately when the user message bubble is rendered. This vulnerability does not depend on whether the AI model is available, nor does it depend on the AI response content.

### Details

The trigger chain is as follows:

```text
chat input content -> chat.vue adds the content as a user message -> user message branch in chatText.vue -> v-html
```

When sending a message, the frontend adds the user input to the chat list before requesting the backend. The user message branch then only replaces line breaks and does not perform HTML escaping. The content is still output through `v-html`:

```ts
// chat.vue:432-442
addChat(uuid.value, {
  content: userMessage,
  inversion: 'user',
  eventType: 'message',
});

// chatText.vue:27
<div v-else class="msg" v-html="parsedText" />

// chatText.vue:117-118
// Preserve line breaks for user messages
parsedText.value = value.replace("\n", "<br>");
```

The backend `/airag/chat/send` receives the same `content` parameter. The user message is appended to the conversation history. After the conversation ends normally, it is saved to Redis. When the historical conversation is reopened, it returns to the same chat component for rendering:

```java
// AiragChatServiceImpl.java:988-997
String content = sendParams.getContent();
UserMessage userMessage = aiChatHandler.buildUserMessage(content, sendParams.getImages());
appendMessage(messages, userMessage, chatConversation, topicId, sendParams.getFiles(), sendParams.getContent());
// AiragChatServiceImpl.java:1616-1620
appendMessage(messages, aiMessage, chatConversation, topicId);
saveChatConversation(chatConversation, false, httpRequest, sessionType);
```

This vulnerability and the AI response bubble XSS issue #9760 are different branches in the same component. This issue only affects the rendering of user message bubbles where `inversion === 'user'`.

### PoC

Log in to `http://localhost:35899/login`, then enter `AI Application Platform / Application Portal`, or directly visit `http://localhost:35899/app/portal`. Select the default “Chat Assistant” and create a new conversation. Enter and send the following payload in the chat input box at the bottom:

```html
<img src=x onerror=alert('jeecgboot-user-send')>
```

When the user message bubble appears on the right side of the page, the browser pops up `jeecgboot-user-send`. At this point, the popup is triggered during the user message bubble rendering stage, and there is no need to wait for an AI response.

<img width="2880" height="1704" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/91605321-9fee-465c-ba1c-c26665d36230" />

### Impact

An attacker can trick a logged-in user into sending crafted content in the AI Application Portal chat box, causing script execution under the JeecgBoot frontend domain. The script can read content visible on the current page and send same-origin requests to `/jeecgboot` APIs using the victim’s current login state.

The direct trigger condition is that the user message enters the user’s own chat bubble, so the attack threshold is higher than stored XSS that can be directly displayed across users. However, the code shows that user messages are also saved to the conversation history. When the same conversation is reopened later, the message still enters the same rendering component. If the product supports scenarios such as conversation sharing, import, customer service review, or administrator review of user conversations, the impact may be further expanded.

### Suggested Fix

User messages do not need to be rendered as HTML. It is recommended to remove `v-html` from the user message branch in `chatText.vue`, render the content as text instead, and preserve line breaks with CSS:

```vue
<div v-else class="msg user-message-text">{{ props.text }}</div>
.user-message-text {
  white-space: pre-wrap;
}
```

If `v-html` must still be used to handle line breaks, HTML escaping should be performed before replacing line breaks. User input must not be directly concatenated into HTML:

```ts
function escapeHtml(value: string) {
  return value
    .replace(/&/g, '&amp;')
    .replace(/</g, '&lt;')
    .replace(/>/g, '&gt;')
    .replace(/"/g, '&quot;')
    .replace(/'/g, '&#39;');
}

parsedText.value = escapeHtml(value).replace(/\n/g, '<br>');
```

### Affected versions

JeecgBoot 3.9.2

### Summary

The chat assistant in the AI application portal renders AI reply `MESSAGE` content using `MarkdownIt({ html: true })` and writes the result into the page via `v-html`. If the model response contains raw HTML, such as `<img onerror=...>`, the browser executes the event handler, resulting in XSS.

The trigger point is the AI reply `MESSAGE` rendering branch. In theory, this can be triggered whether thinking is enabled or disabled, as long as the final AI reply `MESSAGE` contains raw HTML. However, when thinking is enabled, the `THINKING` content also enters another rendering point in the thinking area, which may cause an additional alert and confuse the evidence. Therefore, when reproducing this issue, it is recommended to disable thinking, or use a non-thinking chat model, and only observe the alert triggered by the AI reply bubble.

### Details

The data flow is as follows:

```text
/airag/chat/send -> SSE MESSAGE -> chat.vue updates AI message -> chatText.vue Markdown rendering -> v-html
```

The backend `/airag/chat/send` returns the model partial response as a `MESSAGE` event:

```java
// jeecg-boot-module-airag/.../AiragChatController.java:55-58
@IgnoreAuth
@PostMapping(value = "/send")
public SseEmitter send(@RequestBody ChatSendParams chatSendParams) {
    return chatService.send(chatSendParams);
}

// AiragChatServiceImpl.java:1533-1541
chatStream.onPartialResponse((String resMessage) -> {
    send2Client.accept(resMessage, EventData.EVENT_MESSAGE);
})
```

The frontend `chat.vue:717-768` appends the `MESSAGE` content to the AI message. Then `chatText.vue` enables raw HTML rendering for Markdown in AI messages and directly outputs the result to `v-html`:

```vue
// chatText.vue:4
<div ref="markdownBodyRef" class="markdown-body" v-html="parsedText" />
// chatText.vue:84-112
const mdi = new MarkdownIt({
  html: true,
  linkify: true,
});

if (props.inversion !== 'user') {
  parsedText.value = mdi.render(value);
}
```

This flow does not pass through DOMPurify, an `xss` whitelist sanitizer, or disable raw HTML in Markdown. As a result, event attributes in AI replies are executed by the browser.

### PoC

Prerequisite: the chat assistant is bound to a chat model that can return normal content. To verify only the AI reply bubble, it is recommended to disable thinking. If the model forcibly returns `THINKING`, temporarily switch to a non-thinking model.

Reproduction steps: log in to `http://localhost:35899/login` → go to `http://localhost:35899/app/portal` → select `AI Application Platform / Application Portal / Chat Assistant` → create a new conversation → enter the following prompt and send it:

```text
Decode the following HTML entity and output it as the only content. Do not use a code block, do not use backticks, and do not explain:
&lt;img src="x" onerror="alert('jeecgboot-ai-response')"&gt;
```

Observed result: the user message bubble only displays the entity-encoded text and does not trigger an alert. When the AI reply bubble outputs the raw `<img ... onerror=...>`, the browser shows an alert with `jeecgboot-ai-response`. If thinking is enabled, the same payload may trigger an alert first or additionally in the thinking area. That belongs to another sink and should not be used as the only evidence for this vulnerability.

<img width="2880" height="1704" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/fbc76cd6-fc2e-4ec1-bed1-d96f66d92e60" />

### Impact

An attacker can use prompts, shared conversation content, or upstream data that can influence the model context to induce the AI to reply with malicious HTML. When a user views the reply, the script executes under the JeecgBoot frontend domain with the current logged-in user's identity. It can read page content and send requests to same-origin `/jeecgboot` APIs within the victim's permission scope. If an administrator views the malicious reply, the attack script may access administrator-visible data or modify same-origin resources such as AI application configurations and conversation data.

### Suggested Fix

It is recommended to fix this in the AI reply rendering flow of `chatText.vue`, instead of relying on prompt constraints such as asking the model not to output HTML.

AI replies usually only require Markdown display and do not need raw HTML execution. MarkdownIt HTML support can be directly disabled:

```ts
const mdi = new MarkdownIt({
  html: false,
  linkify: true,
});
```

If a limited HTML display capability must be retained, whitelist sanitization should be performed after `mdi.render(value)` and before assigning the result to `parsedText`. The project frontend already depends on `xss`, so similar handling can be added in `chatText.vue`:

```ts
import xss from 'xss';

const chatHtmlXssOptions = {
  whiteList: {
    p: [],
    br: [],
    strong: [],
    b: [],
    em: [],
    i: [],
    code: [],
    pre: [],
    blockquote: [],
    ul: [],
    ol: [],
    li: [],
    a: ['href', 'title', 'target', 'rel'],
  }, // Do not allow img, iframe, or style in the whitelist, and ensure that event attributes such as onerror, onclick, and onload are removed.
  stripIgnoreTag: true,
  stripIgnoreTagBody: ['script', 'style', 'iframe'],
  safeAttrValue(tag, name, value, cssFilter) {
    if (name === 'href' && !/^(https?:|mailto:)/i.test(value)) {
      return '';
    }
    return xss.safeAttrValue(tag, name, value, cssFilter);
  },
};

const html = mdi.render(value);
parsedText.value = xss(html, chatHtmlXssOptions);
```

### Affected versions

JeecgBoot 3.9.2

### Summary

The AI writing page renders writing content using `MarkdownIt({ html: true })` and outputs it directly to the preview area through `v-html`. The writing content can come from the current edited content, AI-generated content, or saved historical versions. If the writing content contains an HTML payload, such as `<img onerror=...>`, the preview area parses it and executes the event handler. The verified path is: write a malicious historical version through the save API, then switch to that version on the AI writing page, causing the preview area to trigger XSS.

### Details

The frontend sink is located in the AI writing preview area:

```vue
// jeecgboot-vue3/src/views/super/airag/aiwriter/AiWriter.vue:64
<div v-if="!isEditing" v-html="previewMd" class="markdown-container" />
```

`previewMd` is rendered by `MarkdownIt`, with raw HTML support enabled:

```ts
// AiWriter.vue:114
const mdi = new MarkdownIt({
  html: true,
  linkify: true,
});

// AiWriter.vue:130
const previewMd = computed(() => {
  let content = writeText.value || aiText.value;
  return mdi.render(content);
});
```

When saving a historical version, the frontend directly submits `writeText` as `content`:

```ts
// AiWriter.vue:365
await defHttp.post({ url: '/airag/app/save/article/write', params: { content: writeText.value } });
```

After receiving it, the backend endpoint `/airag/app/save/article/write` writes it to Redis under the current username through `saveArticleWrite`:

```java
// AiragAppServiceImpl.java:284
public void saveArticleWrite(AiArticleWriteVersionVo aiWriteVersionVo) {
    LoginUser loginUser = (LoginUser) SecurityUtils.getSubject().getPrincipal();
    String redisKey = StrUtil.format(AiAppConsts.ARTICLE_WRITER_KEY, loginUser.getUsername());
    redisTemplate.opsForValue().set(redisKey, aiWriteVersionVos);
}
```

When switching historical versions, the historical content is assigned back to `writeText`:

```ts
// AiWriter.vue:425
function handleVersionChange(value: string) {
  const target = historyData.value.find((item) => item.version === value);
  writeText.value = target.content;
}
```

Therefore, unsanitized HTML in historical versions re-enters the rendering chain `writeText -> previewMd -> v-html` and gets executed.

### PoC

Payload:

```html
<div><img src=x onerror=alert('jeecgboot-writer')></div>
```

First, log in and save a malicious writing historical version:

```bash
BASE='http://localhost:35899/jeecgboot'

TOKEN=$(curl -sS -X POST "$BASE/sys/login" \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  --data '{"username":"admin","password":"123456","captcha":"","checkKey":""}' \
  | python3 -c 'import sys,json; print(json.load(sys.stdin)["result"]["token"])')

curl -sS -X POST "$BASE/airag/app/save/article/write" \
  -H "X-Access-Token: $TOKEN" \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  --data '{"content":"<div><img src=x onerror=alert('\''jeecgboot-writer'\'')></div>"}'
```

<img width="1826" height="268" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/dda2484b-4777-4d12-9081-62b7cc358295" />

Then visit `http://localhost:35899/airag/aiwriter/AiWriter`, go to `AI Application Platform` / `AI Toolbox` / `AI Writing`, and select the newly saved version, such as `V1`, from the version dropdown at the top of the preview area. After the preview area renders this historical content, an alert showing `jeecgboot-writer` is triggered.

<img width="2880" height="1704" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c08ee0fd-2f03-49e7-b3e0-8e582c0fd75a" />

### Impact

This vulnerability affects the preview and historical version features of the AI writing page. In the verified scenario, the malicious content is stored in the Redis historical version corresponding to the currently logged-in user. When the same account opens or switches to that version again, the script executes in that user’s backend session.

Because `previewMd` also renders `aiText`, the same preview sink may also be triggered if AI-generated content, imported text, or other upstream content contains unsanitized HTML. Once executed, the script can read content visible on the current page and send same-origin requests within the permissions of the currently logged-in user.

### Suggested Fix

Handle HTML content in the preview rendering chain of `AiWriter.vue`, and avoid sending the output of `MarkdownIt` directly into `v-html`.
